          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">US pauses Houthi offensive</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: Oman brokered an agreement with the US and Houthi officials for a ceasefire.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Trump <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-may-25-spotlight-h2-4-announced-a-pause" target="_blank">announced a pause</a> in US airstrikes against Yemen’s Houthi rebels. This followed the Houthis signaling they no longer wanted to fight. Trump said the Houthis had “capitulated” and they will halt attacking ships in the Red Sea. Oman confirmed it helped mediate a ceasefire agreement involving the US and Houthi officials.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          This development comes as efforts to revive nuclear talks with Iran continue. Marco Rubio stated that the US mission is to protect global shipping. Reports suggest that the expenses of the US munitions used against Houthi rebel targets in Yemen in daily attacks since March 15 have totaled more than $750M. Meanwhile, Israel continues strikes on Houthi targets in Yemen after a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-may-25-spotlight-h2-5-missile-landed" target="_blank">missile landed</a> near Tel Aviv.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Houthi leaders welcomed the US pause. However, they vowed to keep attacking Israel in support of Gaza. From November 2023 until January 2025, the Houthis targeted more than 100 merchant vessels, which has reduced the trade through the Red Sea corridor, which typically sees $1T of goods move through it annually.</p>
        </mj-text>
